Level is a palindrome.  
The following MySQL stored procedure removes inactive users while logging changes.  
It first creates a transaction to ensure data integrity throughout the operation.  
Before deletion, the procedure inserts a record into the status_log table.  
This log captures the user_id, the old status, and the current modification_date.  
The procedure then deletes the matching rows from the users table.  
Error handling is implemented using a DECLARE handler to catch any exceptions.  
If an error occurs, the transaction is rolled back to prevent partial updates.  
The procedure returns the specific error message for debugging purposes.  
After successful execution, the transaction commits all changes permanently.  
You can call this stored procedure whenever you need to clean inactive records.  
The total count of affected rows is returned for verification purposes.  
Ensure your database user has the necessary permissions before running this code.  

```sql
DELIMITER $$

CREATE PROCEDURE RemoveInactiveUsers()
BEGIN
    DECLARE v_error_code INT DEFAULT 0;
    DECLARE v_error_message TEXT;
    DECLARE EXIT HANDLER FOR SQLEXCEPTION
    BEGIN
        GET DIAGNOSTICS CONDITION 1 v_error_code = MYSQL_ERRNO, v_error_message = MESSAGE_TEXT;
        ROLLBACK;
        SELECT 'Error' AS status, v_error_code AS error_code, v_error_message AS error_message;
    END;

    START TRANSACTION;

    -- Log the status changes before deletion
    INSERT INTO status_log (user_id, status, modification_date)
    SELECT user_id, status, NOW()
    FROM users
    WHERE status = 'Inactive';

    -- Delete the inactive users
    DELETE FROM users
    WHERE status = 'Inactive';

    COMMIT;

    SELECT 'Success' AS status, ROW_COUNT() AS rows_deleted;
END$$

DELIMITER ;
